A possible solution:
Each square inscribed in the triangle divides the hypotenuse into segments proportional to the adjacent sides: [asy]
pair A=(0,0), B=(5,0), C=(0,3), S1=(0.6,0), S2=(5,0.6);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(S1--S1*(dir(A)+1)--S1*(dir(A)+2)--S1*(dir(C)-1)--S1*(dir(C)-2)--cycle);
draw(S2--S2*(dir(B)+1)--S2*(dir(B)+2)--S2*(dir(C)-1)--S2*(dir(C)-2)--cycle);
label("$A$",A,SW);
label("$B$",B,SE);
label("$C$",C,NW);
label("$S_1$",S1,SW);
label("$S_2$",S2,SE);
[/asy] Thus, we have $\frac{AC}{AB}=\frac{S_1}{S_1+S_2}$ and $\frac{CB}{AC}=\frac{S_2}{S_1+S_2}$.  Combining these equations with the given information that $S_1=441$ yields \begin{align*}
\frac{AC}{AB} &= \frac{441}{441 + CB \cdot AC} \\
\frac{CB}{AC} &= \frac{CB \cdot AC}{441 + CB \cdot AC}
\end{align*} Cross-multiplying and substituting $CB \cdot AC = AC \cdot CB$ results in the equation $AC^2 + CB^2 = AC \cdot CB + 441 \cdot AC$.  Rearranging and factoring gives $(AC - 21)(AC + CB) = 0$.  Since $AC > 0$, we must have $AC = 21$.  Substituting this into the second equation above yields $CB = 21$ as well.  Therefore, $AC + CB = \boxed{42}$.
